          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">
          Lithuanian contingency plans
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/lithuania-evacuation-plan-vilnius-belarus-kaliningrad.png" alt="Map highlighting Lithuania and neighboring regions, Belarus, and Kaliningrad" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Lithuania‚Äôs geography makes it susceptible to a Russian invasion. The country lies between Belarus, a strong Russian ally, and Russian territory along the Baltic Sea.</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           Amid growing concerns over a Russian invasion, officials in Vilnius, Lithuania, have <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-h1-1-announced-an-evacuation-plan" target="_blank">announced an evacuation plan</a> for the city's residents. Vilnius lies 20 miles (35 km) from the border with Belarus, a strong Russian ally, and the country shares a border with Kaliningrad, a heavily fortified Russian exclave.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The evacuation plan includes 150 routes and designated points in each neighborhood. Communication will occur through SMS alerts, sirens, and a mobile app that is currently under development. Roads and bridges will be expanded to allow for smooth evacuation. Mayor Valdas Benkunskas stated that evacuation would be a last resort if the city's defenses fail.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The plan primarily targets military threats but can also be activated in response to natural disasters, nuclear attacks, or infrastructure failures. Lithuania and the other Baltic states are no strangers to Russian threats. These concerns are particularly evident in the context of the Suwa≈Çki Gap (<a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/ps-25-04-2025-h1-2-read-our-earlier-articles" target="_blank">read our earlier article</a>), a strategic corridor that could be disrupted, severing NATO‚Äôs land routes between Poland and the Baltic states.
         </p>
         <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          While threats persist, a Russian invasion of Lithuania is unlikely to succeed under current circumstances. The focus is more on maintaining a contingency plan than on spreading fear.
         </p>
        
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
