          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Muslim Brotherhood getting booted</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/jordan-bans-muslim-brotherhood-announcement.png" alt="Jordan announced on Wednesday that it is banning the Muslim Brotherhood" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;"><i>Jordan announced on Wednesday that it is banning the Muslim Brotherhood. Credits: TOI</i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Jordan announced that <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-h2-3-it-would-ban-the-activities" target="_blank">it would ban the activities</a> of the Muslim Brotherhood, under which it was discovered that the group was moving explosives between cities and storing them in residential neighbourhoods. The decision follows the arrest of 16 individuals, including Brotherhood members, for allegedly plotting sabotage. Authorities also accuse the group of covert operations, like missile manufacturing and recruitment. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Interior Minister Mazen al-Faraya announced that any activity connected to the group is illegal and the authorities will close their offices and seize their assets. The Brotherhood continues its operations in Jordan, despite a 2020 court ruling that dissolved it. They deny involvement in the alleged plot and reassured their support for Jordan's security.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          It remains unclear whether this crackdown will impact the group‚Äôs political arm, the Islamic Action Front (IAF), the major opposition party. The IAF's secretary general, Wael Saqqa, asserted that it was an independent political party and denied any relationship with any other organisational body. </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          The Brotherhood was founded in Egypt almost 100 years ago to create a state ruled by Islamic law. They are outlawed in Egypt and several Arab countries, whose governments see them as a threat.</p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="0px 12px" />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
