            <strong>üá®üá© DRC and M23 agree to 'immediate' ceasefire</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
           The Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and the M23 rebel group, backed by Rwanda, have agreed to pause fighting. After talks in Doha, Qatar, they will work toward a <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-br1-6-broader-peace-deal" target="_blank">broader peace agreement</a>. The truce includes a ceasefire and a ban on hate speech. While the agreement brings some optimism and hopes, ongoing clashes in areas like South Kivu show the vulnerability of the situation. 
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Qatar facilitated a rare meeting between F√©lix Tshisekedi, President of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC), and Paul Kagame, President of Rwanda, which helped initiate the negotiations. Despite tensions over issues such as prisoner releases, both parties agreed to continue the diplomatic talks. </p>
        </mj-text>
