          <p style="font-size:18px;line-height:1.5;">
            <strong>üáßüáØ 54 soldiers killed in suspected Jihadist attack in Benin</strong>
          </p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">Last week, suspected jihadists <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-br2-7-killed-54-soldiers" target="_blank">killed 54 soldiers</a> in Benin, a country in West Africa, at military posts inside the Benin National Park. It is the deadliest assault since jihadist violence began in the northern part of the country. The attack occurred near the borders with Burkina Faso and Niger. The al-Qaeda-linked Group for the Support of Islam and Muslims (GSIM) claimed responsibility.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          Government spokesperson Wilfried Leandre Houngbedji confirmed the toll. He acknowledged the heavy loss and called the fallen soldiers ‚Äúour children, our parents, our friends.‚Äù A similar GSIM-claimed attack in January killed 28 soldiers near the same border area. </p>
        </mj-text>
