          <h2 style="font-size:24px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">Why are there two Congos?
</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image border-radius="10px" padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/republic-democratic-republic-of-congo-map-congo-river-brazzaville-kinshasa.png" alt="Map showing the neighboring countries, the Republic of the Congo and the Democratic Republic of the Congo, located directly across the Congo River" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #A9A7AF;">
          <i>The Congo River divides the Democratic Republic of Congo and the Republic of Congo, and their capitals, Brazzaville and Kinshasa, are the two closest capital cities on Earth. </i></p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">    
           In Central Africa, there are two countries named after the Congo River: the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-f1-8-democratic-republic-of-congo" target="_blank">Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC)</a> and the <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-25-04-2025-f1-9-republic-of-congo" target="_blank">Republic of the Congo</a>.</p>
        
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;"><span style="font-size:18px;font-weight:bold;margin-right:8px">‚Üí</span> <strong>Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC):</strong> Formerly the Belgian Congo, it was colonized by Belgium. It‚Äôs the larger of the two and has Kinshasa as its capital.</p>
            <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;"><span style="font-size:18px;font-weight:bold;margin-right:8px">‚Üí</span><strong>Republic of the Congo:</strong> Previously known as the French Congo, it was colonized by France. Its capital is Brazzaville, located just across the river from Kinshasa.</p>
     
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          During the 1880s, the Congo Basin was divided in half with no regard for the local communities. Both sides of the river had significant cultural overlap. King Leopold II of Belgium ruled one side of the Congo, known as the Congo Free State, as his personal property, while France ruled the other side and called it the French Congo.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          During the 20th Century, the Belgian colony ruled by King Leopold II became the DRC, while the French colony became the Republic of the Congo. After gaining independence in the 1960s, both countries returned to calling themselves Congo. They failed to unify as they were ideological enemies during the Cold War.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          After gaining independence, the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) experienced a series of <a style="text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 2px solid  #06266D; color: black;" href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/ps-25-04-2025-f1-10-proxy-wars" target="_blank">proxy wars</a> before a right-wing dictatorship took control. In 1971, the country was renamed Zaire but reverted to the DRC in 1997. Meanwhile, the neighboring Republic of the Congo came under the rule of a communist junta.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.5;">
          In media coverage, conflicts in the DRC are often referred to simply as occurring in ‚ÄúCongo,‚Äù which can be confusing. The Republic of the Congo, by contrast, has remained relatively more stable.</p>
        </mj-text>
